<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="650" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="31.[2066,2651,1864,2291]" lastBlockId="31.[1449,2652,2301,2880]" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">
<emphasis box="[2067,2323,2021,2054]" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.21" metricValueMax="2.25" metricValueMin="2.17" pageId="31" pageNumber="650" unit="cm" value="22.1" valueMax="22.5" valueMin="21.7">21.7-22.5 cm</quantity>
, tail 
<quantity box="[2196,2390,2061,2094]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1649999999999998" metricValueMax="1.22" metricValueMin="1.1099999999999999" pageId="31" pageNumber="650" unit="cm" value="11.649999999999999" valueMax="12.2" valueMin="11.1">11.1-12.2 cm</quantity>
; weight c. 
<quantity box="[2563,2645,2061,2094]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.38" pageId="31" pageNumber="650" unit="g" value="138.0">138 g</quantity>
. The Columbian Weasel has a long body and short limbs. The pelage is long and soft, almost entirely dark brown on the back, with pale orange undersides. All the feet have extensive webbing, with naked plantar surfaces.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
