<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="650" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="31.[1449,2652,2301,2880]" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">
<emphasis box="[1451,1805,2572,2605]" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Vulnerable in The 
<collectionCode box="[2256,2337,2572,2605]" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">IUCN</collectionCode>
Red List. A very poorly known species, only recently described. Possibly the rarest carnivore in South America, it occurs in a limited area ofless than 
<quantity box="[2035,2178,2659,2684]" metricMagnitude="7" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="650" unit="km" value="10000.0">10,000 km</quantity>
? where deforestation is rampant. Since its discovery, only 
<specimenCount box="[1799,2006,2689,2722]" pageId="31" pageNumber="650" type="generic">five specimens</specimenCount>
have been obtained from western 
<collectingCountry box="[2512,2651,2689,2722]" name="Colombia" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[1651,1730,2733,2762]" country="Colombia" name="Huila" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">Huila</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1806,1894,2733,2762]" country="Colombia" name="Cauca" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">Cauca</collectingRegion>
) and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[2124,2243,2733,2762]" name="Ecuador" pageId="31" pageNumber="650">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. The Columbian Weasel is a high priority for field research to learn more aboutits natural history, ecology, and conservation status.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
